doctors-in-training went on
strike today for the first time
in 40 years.

04:54.427 --> 05:00.734 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The 24-hour walkout was
triggered by a contract dispute
with the government-run National
Health

05:00.734 --> 05:06.039 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Service. The so-called junior
doctors took to the picket lines
to demand better pay for

05:06.039 --> 05:10.877 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
working weekends and to warn
against plans to lengthen their
schedules.

05:10.877 --> 05:15.715 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: I already work up to 24
hours. Many times, that's
nonstop. And I don't really have
any

05:15.715 --> 05:20.353 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
set breaks during the day or the
night. But if those protections
are taken away and the

05:20.353 --> 05:23.823 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
trusts are able to just make us
work for as many hours as they
wish, then, of course,

05:23.823 --> 05:27.761 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we are going to be more tired,
and, ultimately, that's going to
affect patients' safety.

05:27.761 --> 05:32.365 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: About 4,000
operations and outpatient
procedures had to be canceled
due

05:32.365 --> 05:37.571 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to the walkout, but the doctors
still provided emergency care.

05:37.571 --> 05:42.542 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Back in this country, the U.S.
Supreme Court ruled 8-1 the
state of Florida's method of

05:42.542 --> 05:47.747 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
