took last year -- Judy.

11:50.209 --> 11:54.247 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, Lisa, you
have been talking to members up
on the Hill. What are Democrats

11:54.247 --> 11:57.483 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
saying they expect to hear
from the president tonight?

11:57.483 --> 12:01.421 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Democrats, Judy
-- it's interesting -- are
saying this is an entirely
different

12:01.421 --> 12:05.858 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
kind of State of the Union
address. They say it will not be
a wish list of items, not a

12:05.858 --> 12:11.030 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
whole bunch of policy agenda
proposals, but instead a
sweeping vision.

12:11.030 --> 12:14.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's the kind of language
they're using. They say that
this is something that is
forward-looking,

12:14.500 --> 12:17.303 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which is different, of course,
for a president who on his way
out. Usually, those presidents

12:17.303 --> 12:20.873 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
try and recap their
time in office.

12:20.873 --> 12:25.111 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
All of that aside, there is
something Democrats really want
and need from this speech. They

12:25.111 --> 12:29.882 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
need this president to try and
talk up what he's done. And
they're focusing on the economy.

12:29.882 --> 12:34.487 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're hoping that, as 2016 and
many of the members here are
facing reelection, comes

12:34.487 --> 12:38.124 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
up, they want the president to
tout what they say is a strong
performance in the economy

12:38.124 --> 12:40.994 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
under his tenure.

12:40.994 --> 12:45.365 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, we heard
Paul Ryan, the speaker of the
House, a few minutes ago saying

12:45.365 --> 12:49.135 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that he wants to hear what the
president has to say about
fighting terrorism, but you have

12:49.135 --> 12:51.671 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
been talking to other
Republicans. What are they
telling you they look for?

12:51.671 --> 12:54.140 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
LISA DESJARDINS: Right.

12:54.140 --> 12:58.378 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Republicans say two things. Some
strategists that I talked to
outside of this building

12:58.378 --> 13:03.049 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
told me that they think there
could be a chance that, as the
president speaks to his vision,

13:03.049 --> 13:05.551 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
something Democrats want,
Republicans are fine with that
too, because they think his

13:05.551 --> 13:08.254 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
vision helps them.

13:08.254 --> 13:11.691 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're actually -- one person
told me tonight, Judy, that they
think there might be some

13:11.691 --> 13:15.061 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
clips from tonight's speech that
they can run in ads showing that
they think this big

13:15.061 --> 13:18.931 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
government vision, as they see
it, was a failure and is a
failure.

13:18.931 --> 13:22.902 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, on the other hand, when you
talk the Republicans in this
building, they're also

13:22.902 --> 13:27.206 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
playing the forward-looking
game. They're saying they want
to talk about their own vision.

13:27.206 --> 13:32.011 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They say that South Carolina
Governor Nikki Haley is not
going to give a reaction speech

13:32.011 --> 13:35.882 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the Republican response
tonight. She also, they say,
going nontraditional, and will
instead

13:35.882 --> 13:39.585 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
present a Republican vision for
the future, the Republican
agenda.

13:39.585 --> 13:45.191 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But there's a lot of competing
vision optics here as well,
Judy. Democrats told me that

13:45.191 --> 13:50.229 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
