was Saudi-born. Turkey's leaders
also spoke by phone to German

22:28.214 --> 22:32.318 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Chancellor Angela Merkel, who
later addressed reporters in
Berlin.

22:32.318 --> 22:36.956 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ANGELA MERKEL, German Chancellor
(through translator): Today, it
hit Istanbul, but,

22:36.956 --> 22:42.561 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
before that, it was Paris, and,
before that, it was Copenhagen,
Tunisia and so many other

22:42.561 --> 22:47.566 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
places. International terror
chooses the places of its
attacks in different ways, but
its

22:47.566 --> 22:52.538 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
target is always the same: our
life in freedom and our free
societies.

22:52.538 --> 22:57.943 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: This wouldn't
be the first time that ISIS
targeted Turkey. In July, more

22:57.943 --> 23:03.382 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
than 30 people were killed in a
suicide attack in Suruc, near
the southeastern border with

23:03.382 --> 23:09.555 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Syria. Then, in October, twin
suicide bombs exploded at a
peace rally in Ankara. More

23:09.555 --> 23:12.992 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
than 100 were killed.

23:12.992 --> 23:17.696 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Those attacks were aimed at
Turkish Kurds. Their Syrian
brethren are one of the most

23:17.696 --> 23:23.636 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
effective forces fighting ISIS
in Syria. But Kurdish
separatists inside Turkey and
their

23:23.636 --> 23:28.240 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
government are locked in a
vicious new war, after a
two-year cease-fire. Lately,
Turkey

23:28.240 --> 23:33.746 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is taking a stronger hand
in Syria against ISIS.

23:33.746 --> 23:37.549 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Last year, it agreed to open its
bases to U.S. aircraft and to do
more to stop the flow

23:37.549 --> 23:40.653 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of foreign militants into Syria.

23:40.653 --> 23:45.190 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AYLA JEAN YACKLEY: Turkey's also
been more and more outspoken in
its criticism of Islamic

23:45.190 --> 23:50.329 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
State. Maybe initially, there
was some reluctance to call them
terrorists, for example. And

23:50.329 --> 23:55.701 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
now the government officials,
including the president, do call
them terrorists.

23:55.701 --> 24:04.109 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Of course, there's also some
truth to the fact that Turkey
was a very ardent and outspoken

24:04.109 --> 24:09.815 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
opponent and critic of Syrian
President Bashar al-Assad, which
may have encouraged turning

24:09.815 --> 24:15.888 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a blind eye. The idea that
either Turkey, the government,
helped bring this on by not

24:15.888 --> 24:20.392 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
doing enough or has brought it
on by joining the coalition and
maybe doing too much shows

24:20.392 --> 24:24.196 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you the sort of rock and a hard
place that Turkey's caught
between.

24:24.196 --> 24:30.035 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: All of that as
Turkey continues to host more
than two million Syrian
refugees.

24:30.035 --> 24:34.139 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Just yesterday, Ankara said it
will offer refugees work permits
to discourage them from

24:34.139 --> 24:42.881 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
illegally crossing into
the European Union.

24:42.881 --> 24:56.962 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now we turn to
another consequence of the Syria
war, and a weapon used against

24:56.962 --> 25:00.466 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
civilians caught in the middle
of that brutal conflict.

25:00.466 --> 25:04.770 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We begin with a report from
Lindsey Hilsum of Independent
Television News

25:04.770 --> 25:13.212 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LINDSEY HILSUM: It's months
since they ate properly. Are
these tears of hunger or relief?

25:13.212 --> 25:22.855 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Because, finally, after night
fell, food arrived, some of it
to eat right now, no waiting.

25:22.855 --> 25:27.793 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN (through translator): The
situation in Madaya is so bad.
Before the siege, we

25:27.793 --> 25:31.630 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
used to live a proper life, but
when the armed rebels entered
the village and did what they

25:31.630 --> 25:34.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
did, they revealed
their true colors.

25:34.800 --> 25:42.040 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LINDSEY HILSUM: It's a delicate
situation for the U.N. and the
Red Cross and Crescent,

25:42.040 --> 25:47.846 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who are strictly neutral. They
negotiated for months to get
food and medicine into Madaya,

25:47.846 --> 25:52.551 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
besieged by the government, and
two villages besieged by the
rebels, relief for tit for

25:52.551 --> 25:55.087 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
tat starving.

25:55.087 --> 25:58.991 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN (through translator):
People with no electricity are
burning shoes and plastic

25:58.991 --> 26:04.463 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
bags to stay warm. People are in
the street looking for food in
the rubbish.

26:04.463 --> 26:10.235 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LINDSEY HILSUM: This is Madaya
clinic. The few health
professionals left in town were

26:10.235 --> 26:16.074 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
pleased to get badly need
medicines brought by the convoy.
But aid agencies say up to

26:16.074 --> 26:21.146 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
400 people should be evacuated
immediately because they have
serious illnesses that need

26:21.146 --> 26:24.817 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
treatment that's impossible
in these conditions.

26:24.817 --> 26:31.156 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN (through translator): My
son has hepatitis and he has to
leave. I have a medical report

26:31.156 --> 26:35.928 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and I want the take him out.
There are neither medicines, nor
doctors. There is nothing.

26:35.928 --> 26:40.699 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LINDSEY HILSUM: The convoy
succeeded, but the problem is
not solved, and there are dozens

26:40.699 --> 26:43.368 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of besieged places in Syria.

26:43.368 --> 26:47.272 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAWEL KRZYSIEK, International
Committee of the Red Cross:
They're the hardest moments

26:47.272 --> 26:52.845 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to see, to listen to those
people, to hear their concerns,
and to realize that, you know,

26:52.845 --> 26:57.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
one-time distribution will not
solve the long-term problem of
the people living in the
besieged

26:57.716 --> 27:04.423 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
areas, no matter where they are,
in Madaya, Foua and Kefraya,
Deir el-Zour. We just need

27:04.423 --> 27:09.862 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to be able to come back and
bring the aid on a regular
basis.

27:09.862 --> 27:17.236 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LINDSEY HILSUM: So much ruin.
Government barrel bombs have
destroyed the Damascus suburb of

27:17.236 --> 27:24.343 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Zariah (ph), but when they bring
their tanks, the rebels destroy
them.

27:24.343 --> 27:35.721 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And in Idlib today, more Russian
airstrikes; 37 people were
reported killed. As long as

27:35.721 --> 27:40.692 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this goes on, there will be no
real relief for the besieged
people of Syria.

27:40.692 --> 27:45.130 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: For more on the
humanitarian situation in Madaya
and elsewhere in Syria,

27:45.130 --> 27:48.166 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
we turn to William Brangham.

27:48.166 --> 27:51.169 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: As we just
heard in Lindsey Hilsum's
report, the United Nations is
moving

27:51.169 --> 27:55.107 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
aid convoys into the
besieged city of Madaya.

27:55.107 --> 27:59.211 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the very latest on what's
happening there and elsewhere in
Syria, I'm joined via Skype

27:59.211 --> 28:03.215 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
by Kevin Kennedy, the U.N.'s
regional humanitarian
coordinator for the Syria
crisis. He's monitoring

28:03.215 --> 28:05.617 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the situation from
Amman, Jordan.

28:05.617 --> 28:09.121 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, Kevin Kennedy, thank you
very much for being here.

28:09.121 --> 28:12.190 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have seen all of these
terrible images coming out of
Syria. Can you give us the
latest

28:12.190 --> 28:14.326 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
on what's happening in
the town of Madaya?

28:14.326 --> 28:16.395 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KEVIN KENNEDY, U.N. Regional
Humanitarian Coordinator: Well,
as you know, we were able

28:16.395 --> 28:23.535 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to deliver after many months of
requests aid to Madaya last
night for the 42,000 people

28:23.535 --> 28:27.039 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that are trapped there, and also
to two other towns to the north,
Foua and Kefraya.

28:27.039 --> 28:32.377 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we hope to provide some more
deliveries in the next couple
days here, because what

28:32.377 --> 28:35.414 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we were able to do last night
was -- had some of the basic
needs, but much more is required

28:35.414 --> 28:39.418 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
to meet their
situation in Madaya.

28:39.418 --> 28:42.988 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: I mean, we
know that Assad's forces have
surrounded these towns,
sometimes

28:42.988 --> 28:46.191 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
with barbed wire,
sometimes with snipers.

28:46.191 --> 28:48.594 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Have you seen any interference
at all with the aid convoys that
are going into these

28:48.594 --> 28:50.429 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
towns?

28:50.429 --> 28:54.299 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KEVIN KENNEDY: There was a delay
last night, but I would not call
it interference (INAUDIBLE)

28:54.299 --> 28:58.737 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but basically unimpeded. It took
a while to get there, but they
did get there about 8:00

28:58.737 --> 29:01.773 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in the evening and stayed
until 4:00 in the morning.

29:01.773 --> 29:07.980 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I would say this is just one
town of many that are either
besieged or hard to reach

29:07.980 --> 29:14.252 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in Syria. There's about 13.5
million people in need of one
form of humanitarian assistance

29:14.252 --> 29:17.956 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or another in Syria. And about
4.5 million of those are in
these hard-to-reach areas

29:17.956 --> 29:21.126 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and half of those in
ISIL-controlled areas.

29:21.126 --> 29:23.929 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Just as you
say, Amnesty International
referred to Madaya really as

29:23.929 --> 29:26.565 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
just the tip of the iceberg.

29:26.565 --> 29:30.902 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, what are you doing in those
other towns that have been
harder to reach as well?

29:30.902 --> 29:33.939 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KEVIN KENNEDY: Well, we continue
to try to reach them. And we do
in some cases, but not

29:33.939 --> 29:37.042 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
near to the degree
that we should.

29:37.042 --> 29:42.280 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The U.N., the Red Cross, Red
Crescent, the NGOs are very
active on the ground in Syria.

29:42.280 --> 29:45.050 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In fact, it's quite remarkable,
because of the degree of
activity and assistance that's

29:45.050 --> 29:48.854 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
delivered in a very
active war zone.

29:48.854 --> 29:53.992 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Some six million people are fed
every month, every five non-food
items, eight million people

29:53.992 --> 29:58.397 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with clean water, but this is
not meeting the needs that are
there in Syria, particularly

29:58.397 --> 30:01.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
in those areas that are
controlled either by ISIL or
besieged by the armed groups or

30:01.433 --> 30:03.835 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
by the government.

30:03.835 --> 30:08.073 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The United
Nations has passed resolutions
demanding that the Syrian
government

30:08.073 --> 30:12.110 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
allow these aid convoys in, but
there has been very little
success moving the needle

30:12.110 --> 30:15.580 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
there. What other levers do you
have to try to get the aid into
the places where it's

30:15.580 --> 30:17.382 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
needed?

30:17.382 --> 30:21.820 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KEVIN KENNEDY: Well, it's not
just the Syrian government,
though that's one part of the

30:21.820 --> 30:23.321 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
conflict. There's other group as
well, ISIL and other armed
groups that restrict our aid

30:23.321 --> 30:26.825 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
efforts.

30:26.825 --> 30:30.295 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We continue to work with the
government to try to get access.
And we have had some success,

30:30.295 --> 30:35.067 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
not the degree of success that
we would like. We also deliver
from outside the country,

30:35.067 --> 30:40.539 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from Turkey, from Iraq, from
Lebanon and from Jordan as well,
into some of those hard-to-reach

30:40.539 --> 30:43.642 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
areas and negotiate with the
different armed groups there to
get through.

30:43.642 --> 30:48.880 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: My
understanding is that Monday's
delivery and last night's
delivery

30:48.880 --> 30:52.718 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
really will last for about four
weeks. But what happens when
that food runs out? What

30:52.718 --> 30:55.053 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
happens then?

30:55.053 --> 30:57.756 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KEVIN KENNEDY: We will be going
back to the situation you had
before, and the situation

30:57.756 --> 31:01.193 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
was quite dire.

31:01.193 --> 31:08.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is interesting. A kilo of
wheat was going for $89 in
Madaya until yesterday. That
same

31:08.133 --> 31:13.138 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
kilo goes for 75 cents in
Damascus, which gives you an
idea of the degree of
deprivation

31:13.138 --> 31:16.074 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that the people have suffered.
And, of course, the concern is
not only in Madaya, but these

31:16.074 --> 31:18.910 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
other locations, and what
conditions are they in?

31:18.910 --> 31:21.179 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So there are
some supplies in Madaya, but
people just simply can't afford

31:21.179 --> 31:23.381 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to purchase them?

31:23.381 --> 31:25.016 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KEVIN KENNEDY: Well, there is
always a black market in any
war, and there is a black market

31:25.016 --> 31:27.419 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in this war.

31:27.419 --> 31:32.824 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I guess some things leak
into there, not in any great
quantities, but obviously at

31:32.824 --> 31:37.329 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
great expense, and really beyond
the reach of most of the people
to buy them. If the

31:37.329 --> 31:43.268 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
price is 89 times what it should
be, it gives you an idea of the
degree of scarcity and

31:43.268 --> 31:46.471 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the degree of how hard it
is to get these supplies.

31:46.471 --> 31:52.544 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, we have about 15 areas in
Syria that we consider besieged,
and another -- and which

31:52.544 --> 31:57.115 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
contain about 400,000 people,
and another four million people,
if you will, in these

31:57.115 --> 32:01.186 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
hard-to-reach areas where we get
in intermittently, but not with
the consistency and the
sustained

32:01.186 --> 32:03.522 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
effort that we need.

32:03.522 --> 32:09.127 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Some of the
rebel groups have been arguing
that until aid is allowed

32:09.127 --> 32:13.298 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in freely into these towns, that
the peace talks that are planned
for the rest of -- for

32:13.298 --> 32:17.936 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the end of this month shouldn't
go forward. Do you believe that
that's the right strategy?

32:17.936 --> 32:24.109 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KEVIN KENNEDY: You know, we're
calling for immediate, open,
unimpeded and sustained access.

32:24.109 --> 32:29.548 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Of course, we have been calling
on this for years. But this is a
good moment to really

32:29.548 --> 32:33.585 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
put that into play. And I think
all parties in conflict or all
parties going to the peace

32:33.585 --> 32:37.289 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
conference should abide by this.
Meeting the needs of the people,
wherever they may be,

32:37.289 --> 32:42.093 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in whatever area they're under
the control of, is most
important.

32:42.093 --> 32:48.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And denying people the basic
necessities of life and putting
their lives in danger is

32:48.233 --> 32:51.937 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a violation of international
humanitarian law and cannot be
abided by.

32:51.937 --> 32:53.205 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right,
Kevin Kennedy of the United
Nations, thank you very much

32:53.205 --> 32:56.174 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for joining us.

32:56.174 --> 33:05.750 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
KEVIN KENNEDY: Thank you.

33:05.750 --> 33:14.259 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Final deadlines
for college applications are
looming this week, and students

33:14.259 --> 33:17.562 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who are the first in their
family to apply to college are
the least likely to have had

33:17.562 --> 33:21.099 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
help navigating the
complex process.

33:21.099 --> 33:26.905 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A group called the College
Advising Corps is trying to turn
that disparity around. It

33:26.905 --> 33:32.310 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
partners with high schools and
universities to recruit and pay
recent college grads to

33:32.310 --> 33:37.749 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
advise lower-income,
first-generation students on
getting into college.

33:37.749 --> 33:42.487 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Hari Sreenivasan visited two New
York City high schools working
with the corps.

33:42.487 --> 33:44.823 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
VICTORIA DEL TORO, College
Advising Corps: You bought two
movie tickets. Your friend

33:44.823 --> 33:45.724 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
cancels.

33:45.724 --> 33:48.526 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What would you do?

33:48.526 --> 33:50.562 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
STUDENT: I would call
my other friend.

33:50.562 --> 33:51.730 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
VICTORIA DEL TORO: You would
call somebody else. What happens
if that person doesn't

33:51.730 --> 33:53.598 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
respond?

33:53.598 --> 33:57.469 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Many students
at Manhattan Academy for Arts
and Language all still learning

33:57.469 --> 34:02.040 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
English. Most of them are recent
immigrants. The idea of applying
and going to college

34:02.040 --> 34:05.777 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
can feel totally foreign. That's
where Victoria Del Toro comes
in.

34:05.777 --> 34:06.678 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
VICTORIA DEL TORO: Are you going
to lose out on that money?

34:06.678 --> 34:08.546 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
STUDENTS: No.

34:08.546 --> 34:14.152 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
VICTORIA DEL TORO: You call
somebody else. So, colleges work
the same way. So, when they

34:14.152 --> 34:19.124 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
e-mail you, they track who
responds to what. And they want
to know that you're responsible,

34:19.124 --> 34:21.226 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
right?

34:21.226 --> 34:23.962 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: This is her
second full year at the school,
as part of a program called

34:23.962 --> 34:31.202 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
College Advising Corps.

34:31.202 --> 34:35.974 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
As the school's only dedicated
college counselor, her mission
is to have all of the school's

34:35.974 --> 34:41.112 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
nearly 400 students believe
college is an option. It's a
mission that could be
challenging

34:41.112 --> 34:43.915 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in most American high schools.

34:43.915 --> 34:48.119 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, at Manhattan Academy, few
have any friends or relatives
who have experience with
American

34:48.119 --> 34:50.155 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
higher education.

34:50.155 --> 34:54.526 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
VICTORIA DEL TORO: They still
don't think they're performing
at the level that they

34:54.526 --> 35:00.198 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
should be performing at. So,
they're very aware that they are
being compared to other

35:00.198 --> 35:03.802 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
students, and so they know that
the language is a barrier.

35:03.802 --> 35:08.573 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Andrea Ruiz
Diaz came to the U.S. from
Paraguay four years ago. She

35:08.573 --> 35:12.477 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was already convinced college
was in her future, but the
details of how to get there were
a

35:12.477 --> 35:14.412 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
mystery.

35:14.412 --> 35:18.717 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANDREA RUIZ DIAZ, Student: I
wouldn't know about the SATs,
because, when you're an
immigrant

35:18.717 --> 35:22.554 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and you're in America, you're
just focusing on learning the
language, graduating from

35:22.554 --> 35:26.925 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
high school. You're not really
focusing on college yet.

35:26.925 --> 35:33.631 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The type of
help Del Toro provides,
one-on-one help with choosing
schools,

35:33.631 --> 35:37.469 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
help with writing essays, and
guiding students through
completing paperwork, is what
affluent

35:37.469 --> 35:41.573 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
families pay hundreds
of dollars for.

35:41.573 --> 35:47.812 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Across the country, the average
college counselor works with
more than 450 students a year.

35:47.812 --> 35:53.385 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That means the average student
has less than 40 minutes of
individual coaching on college

35:53.385 --> 35:58.456 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
applications. Without partnering
with College Advising Corps,
principal Siv Boletsis says

35:58.456 --> 36:02.360 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
her students would be in the
same boat. Instead, Del Toro
tries to spend 20 to 30 minutes
a

36:02.360 --> 36:04.829 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
week with each student.

36:04.829 --> 36:09.067 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
How important has that
role been on campus here?

36:09.067 --> 36:11.803 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
SIV BOLETSIS, Principal,
Manhattan Academy for Arts and
Language: The two guidance
counselors

36:11.803 --> 36:18.877 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
who are here provide the
socio-emotional support and
programming for the students.
There was

36:18.877 --> 36:25.316 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a need for someone like Victoria
to be here to explain certain
things. These are families

36:25.316 --> 36:28.853 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
who don't know about the college
application process at all.

36:28.853 --> 36:32.924 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Del Toro says
her hours with students and
parents are chipping away

36:32.924 --> 36:37.695 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
at skepticism about the
stressful college application
process being worth it.

36:37.695 --> 36:43.768 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
VICTORIA DEL TORO: My first year
here at Manhattan Academy, it
was definitely not, like, a goal

36:43.768 --> 36:49.007 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
for a student or even a
conversation for a student to
say, hey, I signed up for the
SAT,

36:49.007 --> 36:51.910 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I'm going to take it.

36:51.910 --> 36:59.918 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And now, I must say, like, when
I saw my data and I saw that 94
percent of my senior class

36:59.918 --> 37:03.955 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
registered for the SAT, I said,
things are changing in here.

37:03.955 --> 37:09.327 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: But the goal
is not just to get students to
apply to any college. Aiming

37:09.327 --> 37:14.899 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
high can make a difference. A
growing body of research
suggests low-income,
first-generation

37:14.899 --> 37:20.605 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
students who have the grades to
get into selective schools are
more likely to graduate from
those

37:20.605 --> 37:26.544 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
colleges than from the local,
open-enrollment campuses where
they're still more likely
register.

37:26.544 --> 37:29.848 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VICTORIA DEL TORO: I have more
students applying to private
institutions out of the state
than

37:29.848 --> 37:31.816 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
ever before.

37:31.816 --> 37:35.987 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: In the spring,
Del Toro posts where students
have been accepted and

37:35.987 --> 37:40.492 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the scholarships they have won
on bulletin boards, spurring
competition.

37:40.492 --> 37:44.863 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Andrea Ruiz Diaz says her ideas
about what's possible have
expanded.

37:44.863 --> 37:50.935 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANDREA RUIZ DIAZ: I definitely
wouldn't have considered
applying to schools out of
state.

37:50.935 --> 37:55.440 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Like, I have always had the fear
of going out of my house,
especially because I'm an

37:55.440 --> 38:00.245 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
immigrant. It feels weird and
scary, but she I'm open to it
now.

38:00.245 --> 38:04.449 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AILEEN MONER, College Advising
Corps: There are so many
talented students that don't see

38:04.449 --> 38:07.519 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
themselves competitive enough.

38:07.519 --> 38:11.756 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Aileen Moner
is director of College Advising
Corps' New York office

38:11.756 --> 38:17.028 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
and oversees two-dozen
counselors working in more than
20 high schools across the city.

38:17.028 --> 38:21.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AILEEN MONER: I think we're
definitely working with those
students that maybe don't have

38:21.733 --> 38:27.071 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the social capital to be able to
see themselves on campuses that
-- that they can really succeed

38:27.071 --> 38:28.973 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
in.

38:28.973 --> 38:33.878 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: College
Advising Corps started at the
University of Virginia in 2005.
Today,

38:33.878 --> 38:39.817 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it has more than 500 advisers
working in 14 states. The
students they work with are 30

38:39.817 --> 38:43.321 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
percent more likely to apply to
college and more than 25 percent
more likely to apply

38:43.321 --> 38:46.491 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for financial aid.

38:46.491 --> 38:50.595 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
New York high schools the corps
has worked with over time, like
Eximius College Prep

38:50.595 --> 38:56.701 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the Bronx, are seeing more
students enroll at more
selective four-year colleges.

38:56.701 --> 38:59.470 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Jon Daly partnered with the
Advising Corps when he became
principal of Eximius five years

38:59.470 --> 39:01.439 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
ago.

39:01.439 --> 39:03.041 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JON DALY, Principal, Eximius
College Preparatory Academy:
When I first got here, I
couldn't

39:03.041 --> 39:06.010 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
understand the fact that most of
the students from the South
Bronx here, they were attending

39:06.010 --> 39:09.347 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Staten Island College. That's
where they were going.

39:09.347 --> 39:13.518 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I was really wondering, why
is that happening? Because it's
like a two-hour train ride. and

39:13.518 --> 39:16.788 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it was because a brother or
sister of some of the students
here went there, and then

39:16.788 --> 39:18.890 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it just seemed like that's where
most of the students were going.

39:18.890 --> 39:23.861 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Daly says his
goal for every student is the
best college at the best price.

39:23.861 --> 39:27.765 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JON DALY: Being an immigrant
myself, and being the first
person in my family to go to
college,

39:27.765 --> 39:31.836 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I know firsthand how scary that
process is, and how hard it is
to navigate that. And that's

39:31.836 --> 39:35.873 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
why I was like, we need somebody
here that can demystify this for
the parents.

39:35.873 --> 39:40.044 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: That focus has
given the school a reputation as
a promising avenue

39:40.044 --> 39:44.482 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from the largely low-income
South Bronx to high-quality
colleges.

39:44.482 --> 39:46.184 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JON DALY: We have four years to
get you into the best college.
That's what we will do.

39:46.184 --> 39:48.019 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
All right?

39:48.019 --> 39:52.957 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And the school
is making good on that promise.
Last year, every graduate

39:52.957 --> 39:57.795 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
was admitted to college. Nine of
those 110 grads are at New York
University this year

39:57.795 --> 40:02.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
with full or substantial
financial aid.

40:02.100 --> 40:05.903 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tiffany Marte is one of those
nine. She says a private
university seemed unrealistic
before

40:05.903 --> 40:08.439 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
working with her adviser.

40:08.439 --> 40:12.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TIFFANY MARTE, Student: It was
more of a reach school for me,
and by reach, I mean like
impossible?

40:12.510 --> 40:17.849 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Because it was like -- it was my
dream school. Like, it was in
the city. It had all the class

40:17.849 --> 40:22.520 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
-- all the courses that I wanted
to take, but it wasn't something
that I thought about.

40:22.520 --> 40:26.257 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Her classmate
Jeninne Ware was going to skip
filing extra paperwork for

40:26.257 --> 40:30.028 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
private scholarships. But her
adviser wouldn't let her off the
hook.

40:30.028 --> 40:35.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JENINNE WARE, Student: The
weekend before it was due, I
completed it, because he texted

40:35.933 --> 40:40.171 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
me, and he's like, are you --
did you do it? And I'm like, no,
I'm not going to a private

40:40.171 --> 40:43.508 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
school. So, he really
encouraged me to complete it.

40:43.508 --> 40:47.278 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Without that
prodding, Ware says she wouldn't
be where she is today.

40:47.278 --> 40:57.822 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Hari Sreenivasan in New York.

40:57.822 --> 41:05.396 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Last night, we
told the story of a writing
program for juveniles in a
Chicago

41:05.396 --> 41:08.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
detention center.

41:08.700 --> 41:13.771 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In part two of his report,
Jeffrey Brown profiles a man who
lost his way and then found it
again,

41:13.771 --> 41:16.574 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in prison, through poetry.

41:16.574 --> 41:21.312 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
REGINALD DWAYNE BETTS, Poet: All
our thoughts were beginnings.
And you became the roundness

41:21.312 --> 41:24.615 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that grew to a moon above
your mother's hips.

41:24.615 --> 41:29.153 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: We first met
Reginald Dwayne Betts in Chicago
at the Cook County Juvenile

41:29.153 --> 41:32.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Temporary Detention Facility,
where he'd come to read his
poetry to young inmates and
answer

41:32.757 --> 41:35.059 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
their questions.

41:35.059 --> 41:37.395 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
REGINALD DWAYNE BETTS: If I
never got caught, do I think --
so you're just going to put

41:37.395 --> 41:38.229 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
me on the spot like that?

41:38.229 --> 41:39.630 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

41:39.630 --> 41:42.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Does it take you
back when you walk in a place
like this?

41:42.633 --> 41:45.570 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
REGINALD DWAYNE BETTS: Mostly
no, because it's really
different walking in from the

41:45.570 --> 41:49.040 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
side I walk in now. And so the
reason it takes me back is I
recognize how different the
experience

41:49.040 --> 41:51.142 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
is.

41:51.142 --> 41:52.910 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then, when I see the kids,
though, it takes me back,
because all of them remind

41:52.910 --> 41:55.947 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
me of me when I was younger.

41:55.947 --> 42:00.318 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Betts grew up 700
miles to the east in Suitland,
Maryland, a community

42:00.318 --> 42:02.453 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
southeast of Washington, D.C.

42:02.453 --> 42:05.757 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
REGINALD DWAYNE BETTS: This is
my first time being back in a
while, yes

42:05.757 --> 42:10.228 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: He was a bright
child, an honor student who
loved to read, and had hopes for

42:10.228 --> 42:13.931 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
college, despite being
surrounded by drugs, occasional
violence and peers who'd been
locked

42:13.931 --> 42:15.800 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
up.

42:15.800 --> 42:19.837 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
REGINALD DWAYNE BETTS: I
expected myself to be the
exception, despite the fact that
I

42:19.837 --> 42:23.408 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
smoked weed, just like everybody
else, and I kind of hung around
out here late at night,

42:23.408 --> 42:26.310 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
just like everybody else. I
guess I thought I would end up
different.

42:26.310 --> 42:28.780 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Why?

42:28.780 --> 42:31.082 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
REGINALD DWAYNE BETTS: I thought
I was smart. I thought I was
better. I thought I could

42:31.082 --> 42:35.987 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
beat the odds, maybe. And I
thought the stuff that I was
doing wasn't that bad anyway.

42:35.987 --> 42:41.959 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: That all changed
on the evening of December 7,
1996, at this mall in
Springfield,

42:41.959 --> 42:46.197 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Virginia, when then 16-year-old
Betts and a friend used a gun to
rob a man and steal

42:46.197 --> 42:48.666 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
his car.

42:48.666 --> 42:53.237 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
REGINALD DWAYNE BETTS: I
recognized carjacking was wrong
and it was crazy, but, in the
spur

42:53.237 --> 42:57.708 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of the moment, I just didn't
think about it at all.

42:57.708 --> 43:01.779 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Betts was
arrested the very next day. It
was his first run-in with the

43:01.779 --> 43:06.717 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
law. He was transferred to adult
court and later given a
nine-year sentence.

43:06.717 --> 43:11.122 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, you go to prison, you're a
teenager, and you're among
adults.

43:11.122 --> 43:12.290 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
REGINALD DWAYNE BETTS: Yes.

43:12.290 --> 43:14.258 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Scary?

43:14.258 --> 43:19.163 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
REGINALD DWAYNE BETTS: Yes. I
couldn't go and bring my mom
water late at night if she

43:19.163 --> 43:22.667 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
wanted water. I didn't have my
own bed to sleep in. So that was
part of being terrified,

43:22.667 --> 43:26.771 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is just what it meant for now
being an adult and to be on my
own.

43:26.771 --> 43:31.075 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then the other part of being
terrified, I think, was just
partly prison is a dangerous

43:31.075 --> 43:33.377 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and scary place, and you never
know what's going to happen
from, you know, one moment

43:33.377 --> 43:35.480 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to the next.

43:35.480 --> 43:40.618 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Reading became a
comfort, and one day changed his
life altogether when he

43:40.618 --> 43:44.755 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
was handed a copy of Dudley
Randall's "The Black Poets," an
anthology that would open

43:44.755 --> 43:47.992 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
his eyes to the
possibilities of poetry.

43:47.992 --> 43:50.895 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
What did it give you,
being there in prison?

43:50.895 --> 43:54.165 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
REGINALD DWAYNE BETTS: Well, the
poetry gave me ability to access
the world and communicate

43:54.165 --> 43:57.301 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
my ideas and my feelings
about the world.

43:57.301 --> 44:02.773 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, also, it was my idea of how
to be somebody. Being a poet,
for me, was being somebody.

44:02.773 --> 44:08.179 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it gave me something to
pursue, and I could easily tell
when I was doing it right

44:08.179 --> 44:13.351 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by people's response. And, also,
I just really admire poets,
Etheridge Knight, Sonia Sanchez,

44:13.351 --> 44:19.690 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Robert Hayden, Amiri Baraka,
Jack Gilbert, Agha Shahid Ali,
just people who I found able

44:19.690 --> 44:23.094 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to say something to me about a
world that I didn't know in
verse, and I just aspired

44:23.094 --> 44:25.863 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to be able to do that.

44:25.863 --> 44:30.301 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: After getting out
of prison, Betts attended
community college, taught middle

44:30.301 --> 44:35.506 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
school, and earned his
undergraduate and master's
degrees. And he wrote, a memoir
and two books

44:35.506 --> 44:40.678 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of poetry. The latest is titled
"Bastards of the Reagan Era."

44:40.678 --> 44:44.749 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The poems, he says, speak of a
generation of black men lost to
drugs, violence and long

44:44.749 --> 44:46.851 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
prison terms.

44:46.851 --> 44:50.254 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
REGINALD DWAYNE BETTS: So lost
in terms of maybe not coming up
with a father in the house,

44:50.254 --> 44:53.558 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but, more significantly, lost in
a way in which -- almost as if
the larger community

44:53.558 --> 44:56.093 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
has abandoned you.

44:56.093 --> 44:59.830 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, we can look around,
and we can look at the
playground. We could go to the
schools

44:59.830 --> 45:03.034 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and look at the school system,
and we could ask ourselves what
kind of opportunities were

45:03.034 --> 45:06.103 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
available for this kid
or that kid or that kid.

45:06.103 --> 45:09.407 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
"For the City That
Nearly Broke Me."

45:09.407 --> 45:15.913 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
"No indictment follows Malik's
death, follows smoke running
from a fired pistol. An old

45:15.913 --> 45:22.486 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
quarrel, crimson against
concrete and the officer's gun
still smoking. Someone says

45:22.486 --> 45:29.160 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the people need to stand up,
that the system's a glass house
falling on only a few heads."

45:29.160 --> 45:33.431 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When I talk in D.C., a lot of
the poems were written when I
was teaching in Southeast.

45:33.431 --> 45:36.701 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I was teaching in Hart Middle
School. And some of the poems
come out of that experience,

45:36.701 --> 45:41.305 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
just thinking about how
sometimes that it's just
overwhelmingly difficult.

45:41.305 --> 45:48.446 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, in fact, I had more moments
of just heartbreak, I think, and
tragedy teaching than I did in

45:48.446 --> 45:53.050 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
prison. And so, in those poems,
I think I'm fixating on the
thing that causes me so much

45:53.050 --> 45:59.223 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
pain, not to the exclusion of
everything else, but to the
point that I really want to have

45:59.223 --> 46:04.729 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to confront what it means to
meet somebody that you really
think is brilliant, and know

46:04.729 --> 46:11.035 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that it might not pan out
for them the way you want.

46:11.035 --> 46:17.208 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Betts himself is
now finishing law school at Yale
University. And he's also

46:17.208 --> 46:21.078 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
an advocate for prison reform,
particularly for the treatment
of juveniles.

46:21.078 --> 46:23.814 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
REGINALD DWAYNE BETTS: The
question is, do some people have
to get locked up to get to

46:23.814 --> 46:26.150 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that certain point where they
can make themselves better in
life?

46:26.150 --> 46:29.453 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And serves on the
White House Coordinating Council
on Juvenile Justice and

46:29.453 --> 46:32.056 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Delinquency Prevention.

46:32.056 --> 46:38.329 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When it came up when we were
together in Chicago from some of
the young inmates there, in a

46:38.329 --> 46:42.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
sense, was it better for you to
go to prison? You started
reading, you started writing.

46:42.500 --> 46:44.869 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Everything that's happened
to you since came from that.

46:44.869 --> 46:48.239 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
REGINALD DWAYNE BETTS: Yes, so I
guess I tend to push back on
that.

46:48.239 --> 46:53.144 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I was fortunate in a lot of
ways. Like, I was safe in
prison, and you can't bank on

46:53.144 --> 46:58.616 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
being safe in prison. You know,
you could say that prison was
the catalyst for all that,

46:58.616 --> 47:01.786 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and I think that that would be
true, but there's also an
argument to be made that, for
that

47:01.786 --> 47:06.123 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to happen, a lot of things had
to fall in place in a perfect
way.

47:06.123 --> 47:10.327 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I always say that what that
signals is not the benefit of
prison, but what that signals

47:10.327 --> 47:16.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is the dearth of opportunities
and the dearth of imagination in
the lives of a lot of young

47:16.100 --> 47:23.107 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
folks, that, really, we have to
rely on things like institutions
to supply the notion that

47:23.107 --> 47:28.012 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- not that you could rise above
your circumstances, but that
your circumstances should
include

47:28.012 --> 47:31.215 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
something more, that your
circumstances should include
being a writer.

47:31.215 --> 47:33.918 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: And
what is the plan now?

47:33.918 --> 47:36.253 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
REGINALD DWAYNE BETTS: The
plan now, to be a lawyer.

47:36.253 --> 47:37.154 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: To be a lawyer.

47:37.154 --> 47:39.056 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
REGINALD DWAYNE BETTS:
To be a lawyer.

47:39.056 --> 47:43.494 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I want to try to solve big
problems. Somebody told me
yesterday that you don't go to
Yale

47:43.494 --> 47:49.567 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Law School to play it safe. And
he said, despite the fact that
you got three felonies, you're

47:49.567 --> 47:54.004 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
playing with house money, and
you need to make a decision
about what you could do that's

47:54.004 --> 47:57.942 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
actually ambitious and test the
possibilities of the world. And
can you think of ways to

47:57.942 --> 47:58.843 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
solve big problems?

47:58.843 --> 48:01.212 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And writing?

48:01.212 --> 48:04.115 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
REGINALD DWAYNE BETTS: And
writing, always writing. Writing
is like breathing, so always

48:04.115 --> 48:06.751 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
writing, always writing.

48:06.751 --> 48:11.288 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: From Suitland,
Maryland, I'm Jeffrey Brown for
the "PBS NewsHour."

48:11.288 --> 48:16.494 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The first part of
Jeffrey Brown's report looks at
a writing program in one of

48:16.494 --> 48:30.508 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the nation's largest juvenile
detention facilities. That's on
our Web site at
PBS.org/NewsHour.

48:30.508 --> 48:39.617 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Finally, another installment in
our series of "NewsHour" essays,
a long tradition of

48:39.617 --> 48:42.520 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the "NewsHour" that we
have resurrected recently.

48:42.520 --> 48:46.323 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Tonight, we hear from Nicholas
Thompson, the editor of "The New
Yorker" magazine's Web

48:46.323 --> 48:50.461 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
site, NewYorker.com.

48:50.461 --> 48:54.832 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We hear a lot these days about
how the Internet, social media,
and our addictive use of our

48:54.832 --> 48:59.036 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
handheld devices are reducing
our attention spans.

48:59.036 --> 49:04.241 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
But, in tonight's essay,
Thompson takes a distinctly
different point of view.

49:04.241 --> 49:06.844 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NICHOLAS THOMPSON, "The New
Yorker": The word story is a
shortening of the word history

49:06.844 --> 49:10.447 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and derives from the work of
Herodotus 2,500 years ago.

49:10.447 --> 49:15.152 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He wanted people to understand
the collision between the Greek
and Persian worlds, and

49:15.152 --> 49:18.956 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
he wanted us to enjoy reading
what he wrote. The opening of
first book describes money,

49:18.956 --> 49:23.427 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
sex, violence, and kidnapping.

49:23.427 --> 49:28.032 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For most of human history,
storytelling helped humans
survive. The societies that
first learned

49:28.032 --> 49:31.635 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to write kept better records,
planned their expeditions more
carefully, and described

49:31.635 --> 49:35.239 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the faraway lands they
would soon plunder.

49:35.239 --> 49:39.577 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Meanwhile, technology enabled
storytelling. Sharing stories is
easier when you can write

49:39.577 --> 49:44.882 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
them down or when you can print
and bind them. Now, however, as
you may have heard, storytelling

49:44.882 --> 49:49.386 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is under threat. The Internet is
shortening our attention spans,
distracting us, quite

49:49.386 --> 49:53.524 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
possibly muddling the
structures of our brains.

49:53.524 --> 49:58.128 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I started writing long magazine
stories about 15 years ago,
right about when one of the

49:58.128 --> 50:03.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
main publishers of long magazine
stories, "Rolling Stone,"
declared it was abandoning

50:03.400 --> 50:07.071 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
them. "I don't think people have
time to sit down and read," the
editor declared. And that

50:07.071 --> 50:10.274 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
was before Twitter.

50:10.274 --> 50:14.879 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In 2008, Nicholas Carr published
his seminal essay, "Is Google
Making Us Stupid?" People,

50:14.879 --> 50:19.250 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
he argued, have lost the ability
to read deeply. We can only
skim, bouncing between
hyperlinks,

50:19.250 --> 50:21.418 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
distracted by beliefs.

50:21.418 --> 50:25.389 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He bemoaned the fact that The
New York Times had started to
publish more and more news

50:25.389 --> 50:29.793 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
summaries. Carr later expanded
his article into a book, making
the same argument, but

50:29.793 --> 50:34.498 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
more intensely. He called
it "The Shallows."

50:34.498 --> 50:39.169 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Since then, you might think, the
argument has been vindicated.
Look at the Internet.

50:39.169 --> 50:44.008 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's plagued by short, shallow
rewrites of gibberish. We buy
books, but we don't read

50:44.008 --> 50:46.210 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
them. Five years from now,
something will have been
invented that makes tweets seem

50:46.210 --> 50:48.646 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
long and ponderous.

50:48.646 --> 50:53.851 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
But, actually, look more
closely. The New York Times did
start publishing additional

50:53.851 --> 50:58.689 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
news summaries back then, but,
ever since, it has shifted huge
amounts of energy to long-form

50:58.689 --> 51:02.126 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
journalism. Even the criminals
in this tale, The Huffington
Post and BuzzFeed, have started

51:02.126 --> 51:05.195 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
doing their own long form work.

51:05.195 --> 51:09.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
"Rolling Stone" is back in it,
for better or worse. "The New
Yorker" continues to run

51:09.266 --> 51:12.703 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
long stories every week. Likely
the best-read piece in the
history of the magazine's Web

51:12.703 --> 51:17.841 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
site is a 24,000-word
piece on Scientology.

51:17.841 --> 51:23.113 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The editors of longform.org get
classic referrals from the
dating site OkCupid, meaning
that

51:23.113 --> 51:28.052 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
people are listing their love
of the site on their profiles.

51:28.052 --> 51:33.624 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Meanwhile, television has
evolved toward almost endless
and overwhelming complexity. The
shows

51:33.624 --> 51:38.595 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that define the '60s, '70s and
'80s, "Cheers," "The Simpsons"
or "Seinfeld," are cream cheese

51:38.595 --> 51:43.434 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
bagels compared to the full
meals offered by "The Sopranos,"
"Breaking Bad," or "Games

51:43.434 --> 51:47.237 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of Thrones." And I should add
that the latter show is, of
course, based upon a series of

51:47.237 --> 51:53.310 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
books written by George R.R.
Martin that cumulatively run
about 5,000 pages.

51:53.310 --> 51:58.148 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So what's happening? Technology
takes our time away, but it also
gives it back. Our

51:58.148 --> 52:02.820 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
smartphones, our computers, our
connection speeds make it
possible to process and absorb

52:02.820 --> 52:06.256 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ever more information. We have
near infinite memories. It's
become easier to write, and

52:06.256 --> 52:09.259 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
it's become easier to read.

52:09.259 --> 52:13.697 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's something deeply human
about storytelling. It's part of
how we learn language as babies,

52:13.697 --> 52:17.901 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and it's part of how we come to
understand our world as adults.
The intelligence of humans

52:17.901 --> 52:21.338 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
is best thought of as a
combination of ourselves and our
machines.

52:21.338 --> 52:26.310 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And looked at this way, you
realize we're becoming smarter
and smarter every day. We

52:26.310 --> 52:30.247 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
don't have as much free time as
we used to, and the Internet has
created all kinds of

52:30.247 --> 52:34.585 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
terrible habits. Just try to
avoid checking your e-mail when
this ends.

52:34.585 --> 52:40.157 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But complexity surrounds us and
beckons us. It's hard not to
think that Herodotus would

52:40.157 --> 52:46.764 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
be proud.

52:46.764 --> 52:54.805 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Before we go
tonight, in the last few
minutes, the White House has
released

52:54.805 --> 52:59.243 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
excerpts from tonight's State of
the Union address that the
president will be delivering

52:59.243 --> 53:03.680 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to Congress in the coming hours.
The sections made public
highlight a vision for the
future

53:03.680 --> 53:07.618 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that includes healing the
current political divide.

53:07.618 --> 53:13.357 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Mr. Obama is expected to say --
quote -- "The future we want,
opportunity and security for

53:13.357 --> 53:19.296 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
our families, a rising standard
of living and a sustainable,
peaceful planet for our

53:19.296 --> 53:24.001 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
kids, all that is within our
reach. But it will only happen
if we work together. It will

53:24.001 --> 53:28.172 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
only happen if we fix our
politics" -- end quote.

